---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Patient Management & Appointment System — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped a Melbourne multi-specialist clinic replace paper appointment books, fax referrals and disconnected billing with a fully integrated digital practice management platform — cutting no-shows by 67% and saving 3+ weeks of admin time per year.',
  industry: 'Healthcare',
  tags: ['React', 'FastAPI', 'PostgreSQL', 'Twilio SMS', 'Medicare Integration'],
  title: 'Patient Management & Appointment System',
  summary: 'A Melbourne multi-specialist clinic had been running on paper appointment books, fax-based referral intake and a billing system with no connection to anything else for over a decade. We replaced it all with a single integrated platform — and gave the admin team their mornings back.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Split-screen showing the appointment calendar view on desktop alongside the SMS reminder flow on mobile, with a patient intake form in the background',

  clientOverview: 'A Melbourne specialist clinic operating for eleven years, housing a cardiologist, gastroenterologist and dermatologist under one roof. The practice sees approximately 180 patients per week across all three specialists and employs four full-time administrative staff. The clinic had grown steadily through GP referrals and reputation, but its operational infrastructure had not kept pace with that growth.',
  clientSize: '3 specialists, 4 admin staff, ~180 patients/week',
  clientLocation: 'Melbourne, VIC',

  pullQuote: 'The billing reconciliation used to eat most of my Tuesday morning. Now it takes me twenty minutes and I actually trust the numbers.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Practice Manager',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Melbourne Specialist Clinic',

  challenge: [
    'When the practice manager first reached out, the phrase she used was "organised chaos." On the surface, the clinic ran smoothly — patients were seen, bills were paid, referrals were followed up. But the infrastructure holding it all together was a patchwork of habits, paper trails and institutional knowledge held by individual staff members. If someone took sick leave, the whole system became fragile.',
    'Appointments were managed across three separate paper books — one per specialist — with no shared visibility. If a patient needed to see two of the three doctors on the same day, coordinating that involved physically walking between books and hoping nothing had been written ambiguously. Double bookings happened. Gaps appeared that should have been filled. The receptionist who had been there longest had developed an almost encyclopaedic memory for which patients preferred morning slots and which GPs sent referrals for which specialist — none of that knowledge existed anywhere except in her head.',
    'Referral intake was entirely fax-based. Incoming faxes were printed, sorted into trays, manually transcribed into a spreadsheet to track their status, and then filed. The transcription step alone introduced errors — names misspelt, Medicare numbers entered incorrectly, referral expiry dates missed. When a GP\'s receptionist called to follow up on a referral, the clinic staff had to physically locate the paper to answer the question. On busy days, that wasn\'t always quick.',
    'Billing was handled in a completely separate desktop application that had no connection to the appointment system. After each consultation, the doctor\'s notes — scanned to PDFs and stored in folder structures on a local server — were cross-referenced manually to generate invoices. Medicare and private health fund claims were submitted separately, often at the end of the week, meaning reconciliation was a significant task. Errors in billing codes occasionally resulted in delayed or rejected claims that went unnoticed for weeks. The practice manager estimated she spent three hours every Tuesday on billing reconciliation alone.',
    'Patient reminders were done by phone call. Every afternoon, a staff member would work through the next day\'s appointments and call each patient. This took between 90 minutes and two hours depending on how many patients answered first time versus required a callback. Despite this effort, the no-show rate was sitting at approximately 22% — meaning roughly 40 appointment slots per week were lost, most of them unrecoverable at short notice.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The clinic\'s practice manager had spoken to two other development firms before contacting us. One had proposed building a custom system from scratch on a timeline she described as "unrealistically ambitious," with a fixed-price contract that excluded any changes once development started. The other had recommended a large off-the-shelf practice management platform — which would have solved some problems but not the specific integrations they needed, and came with per-seat licensing that would have cost more annually than they wanted to spend on the entire project.',
    'What the clinic needed was someone who understood both the technical problem and the practical constraints of running a small specialist practice. We\'d worked on healthcare systems before and had direct familiarity with Medicare bulk billing claim structures, ADHA My Health Record API considerations, and the particular sensitivity required when handling patient data. The practice manager appreciated that we asked about workflows before we talked about technology — and that we were honest about which parts of what she was asking for were straightforward and which parts would require careful testing before going live.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'We spent the first two weeks doing nothing but listening and documenting. We sat with each admin staff member individually and walked through their typical day in detail. We asked them to show us every piece of paper that passed through their hands, every screen they opened, every workaround they\'d invented. We wanted to understand not just what the system did, but why it did it that way and what would break if we changed it.',
    'One of the most useful things we learned early was that the existing "chaos" had a logic to it. The paper appointment books, for instance, had physical annotations — coloured stickers, circled names, sticky notes — that encoded information the staff found genuinely useful. Any new system had to replicate that expressiveness digitally, or the staff would resist it. We catalogued every annotation type and made sure the digital calendar could represent all of them.',
    'We proposed a phased approach rather than a big-bang cutover. Phase one was the appointment and patient management system. Phase two was SMS reminders and digital referral intake. Phase three was billing integration. This let the clinic start realising value early, gave the staff time to adjust to each change, and meant that if something in phase one wasn\'t quite right, we could correct it before building dependent features on top of it.',
    'Before writing a line of code, we built a clickable prototype of the appointment calendar and walked the entire admin team through it. This generated a list of about 35 change requests — most of them small, a few significant. We\'d budgeted time for this. Getting that feedback before development started was far cheaper than making changes during or after.',
    'We were also clear with the client about what we were not doing in scope. The ADHA My Health Record API was discussed — it would theoretically allow the system to pull patient summaries directly from the national record — but after examining the certification requirements and implementation complexity, we agreed to mark it as a future phase and not to design the system in a way that prevented it later, rather than rushing integration that might not work correctly.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The core of the system is a React single-page application that serves as the daily working environment for all four admin staff. The appointment calendar is the primary view — a week-at-a-glance layout that shows all three specialists\' schedules simultaneously, with colour coding by appointment type and status. Staff can drag and drop appointments to reschedule, see a patient\'s full history with a single click, and add the kinds of annotations the old paper books had — urgency flags, preferred contact times, GP referral status.',
    'Patient records are stored in PostgreSQL and include everything that previously existed across scattered systems: personal and contact details, Medicare number, private health fund membership, referral history, appointment history, consultation notes (still scanned PDFs at the clinic\'s request, but now linked directly to the patient record and indexed), and billing status. The intake form for new patients is a web form that can be sent via SMS link before the first appointment, meaning patients fill it out at home and it populates the record automatically. What previously took 15 minutes at the front desk now takes four.',
    'The SMS reminder system was built on Twilio. Two days before each appointment, the system sends a reminder with a confirmation link. Patients who do not confirm within 24 hours receive a follow-up. Cancellations trigger an automatic prompt to the admin interface suggesting patients from the waitlist who could fill the slot. The entire daily call routine — which consumed two hours of an admin staff member\'s afternoon — no longer happens. The reminder process runs automatically overnight.',
    'Referral intake was redesigned around email rather than fax. Referring GPs can send referrals to a dedicated intake email address, where they are parsed and entered into the system as pending referrals. For practices still using fax, the fax machine outputs to a digital fax service that delivers to the same email inbox. The admin team reviews a queue of incoming referrals each morning rather than sorting a physical tray, and can mark them as accepted, pending appointment, or requiring follow-up. Status is tracked in the system, meaning any staff member can answer a follow-up call without needing to locate a physical document.',
    'Billing integration was the most technically complex part. The clinic uses a Medicare-registered billing provider, and we integrated with their API to submit claims directly from the appointment record. After a consultation is marked as complete, the doctor\'s billing code is entered (a step the doctors themselves do on a simple mobile interface), and the claim is queued for submission. Reconciliation reports are generated automatically and show any claims with errors or rejections flagged for review. The practice manager\'s three-hour Tuesday morning is now a 20-minute review.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'The transition from paper to digital was the part we were most careful about. We ran the old and new systems in parallel for six weeks. During that time, appointments were entered into both the paper books and the new system every day. At the end of each day, a staff member reconciled the two. This was extra work in the short term, but it meant that when errors occurred in the new system — and they did, mostly edge cases in appointment conflict detection — they were caught and corrected before anyone was relying on the system exclusively.',
    'Training happened in small groups over two days, with role-specific sessions. The receptionist who handled most of the daily scheduling got the most time with the calendar features. The staff member who managed referral intake worked through a set of simulated scenarios. The practice manager was walked through the billing and reporting views in detail. We also created a laminated quick-reference card for each role — not a comprehensive manual, but the five or six things each person would most likely need to look up in the first few weeks.',
    'We remained available for the first four weeks after go-live via a dedicated Slack channel. This was not a support desk — it was direct access to the developers. Questions that came in were almost always about workflow rather than bugs: "What happens if a patient needs to reschedule but the referral is about to expire?" or "Can I see which GP has sent the most referrals this month?" Some of those questions prompted small feature additions. A few prompted us to rethink how we\'d presented certain workflows. All of them were useful.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'We underestimated how much the parallel-running period would surface about edge cases in the appointment conflict detection logic. Multi-specialist practices have genuinely complex scheduling constraints — a patient who sees both the cardiologist and gastroenterologist on the same day needs a gap, certain procedure types need longer slots, some appointment types can\'t be the last of the day. We\'d modelled most of these correctly, but the six-week parallel period revealed three scenarios we\'d missed. We were glad we\'d built in that buffer.',
    'The fax-to-email transition was less seamless than we\'d hoped for some referring practices. A few GP clinics had fax machines that produced image quality too poor for reliable digital delivery, and a small number of referring doctors were uncomfortable with the change initially. The client\'s practice manager handled the GP relationship side of this herself, which was the right call — these were professional relationships she\'d maintained for years. Our job was to make sure the system worked once they came on board, not to manage the clinical network.',
    'One decision we made early — storing consultation notes as PDFs linked to patient records rather than building a full clinical notes system — was the right call for this project but created a mild limitation. The notes are not searchable by content, only by patient and date. The clinic has asked whether we can add OCR-based indexing in a future phase, and we\'ve scoped it. It would be straightforward to add. But it was the right call to leave it out of scope for v1 rather than delaying launch.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'Within six months of go-live, the clinic asked us to build a patient-facing portal — a simple web application where patients can view their upcoming appointments, download referral letters, and update their contact details. This was a natural extension of the system we\'d already built. We\'d designed the data model with this in mind, so the portal was a relatively thin layer on top of existing APIs.',
    'There are two items on the roadmap for the next twelve months: integration with the ADHA My Health Record API (now that the clinic has seen the system work reliably and is willing to invest in the certification process), and an outcomes tracking module that would let the practice run simple aggregate reports on patient outcomes over time — useful for the specialists\' professional development requirements.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'The numbers tell part of the story, but the part that matters most to the practice manager is that the clinic feels different to work in. The admin team starts each day knowing exactly what is scheduled, who is confirmed, and what referrals need attention — rather than spending the first hour reconstructing the day\'s picture from paper and memory. That shift in how the working day begins has had an effect on the whole team\'s confidence.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '67%', label: 'Reduction in no-shows', context: 'From ~22% to ~7% after SMS reminder system launch' },
    { value: '2 hrs/day', label: 'Reclaimed from reminder calls', context: 'Daily phone reminder routine fully replaced by automated SMS' },
    { value: '20 min', label: 'Weekly billing reconciliation', context: 'Down from 3 hours every Tuesday morning' },
    { value: '4 min', label: 'New patient intake time', context: 'Down from 15 minutes at the front desk' },
    { value: '99.2%', label: 'Appointment data accuracy', context: 'Measured over first 6 months vs estimated ~94% on paper' },
    { value: '3.1 wks', label: 'Admin time saved per year', context: 'Aggregate across all 4 admin staff roles' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'React', reason: 'Rich interactive calendar and patient record UI with complex state requirements' },
    { name: 'FastAPI', reason: 'Python backend chosen for its performance and clean async support for Twilio and billing API calls' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Relational structure suited to the complex appointment, patient and referral relationships' },
    { name: 'AWS (RDS + EC2 + S3)', reason: 'Hosted in Sydney region; S3 for PDF consultation notes storage with encryption at rest' },
    { name: 'Twilio SMS', reason: 'Reliable SMS delivery for appointment reminders with read receipts and reply parsing' },
    { name: 'Stripe', reason: 'Private billing payments and gap fee collection for non-bulk-billed consultations' },
    { name: 'Medicare Billing API', reason: 'Direct claim submission via the clinic\'s registered billing provider API' },
    { name: 'Digital Fax (eFax)', reason: 'Bridged legacy fax-based referral intake into digital email queue without requiring GP practice changes' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: 'Telehealth Platform for GP Practice',
      href: '/case-studies/telehealth-platform-gp',
      industry: 'Healthcare',
      summary: 'A suburban Brisbane GP practice extended its reach to regional Queensland patients through a bulk-billing-compliant telehealth platform handling 300+ consultations per week.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Prescription Tracker & Medication Reminder App',
      href: '/case-studies/prescription-tracker-medication-app',
      industry: 'Healthcare',
      summary: 'A Perth compounding pharmacy built a patient-facing mobile app with medication reminders and dispensing software integration that improved adherence rates by 44%.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Document Management & Approval Workflow System',
      href: '/case-studies/document-management-approval-workflow',
      industry: 'Government',
      summary: 'A state government department reduced average document approval time from 11 days to 2.5 days with a fully digital workflow and audit trail.',
    },
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: 'Custom App Development', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
    { title: 'API Development & Integration', href: '/services/api-development' },
    { title: 'Healthcare Software', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
